---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "The Complete Guide to Bread Baking (From First Loaf to Sourdough)",
      "description": "Everything about bread baking: sourdough starters, hydration, baker's percentages, kneading techniques, fermentation science, and troubleshooting common problems.",
      "image": "https://28grams.vip/og-image.jpg",
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "28grams"
      },
      "publisher": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "28grams",
        "logo": {
          "@type": "ImageObject",
          "url": "https://28grams.vip/logo.png"
        }
      },
      "mainEntityOfPage": {
        "@type": "WebPage",
        "@id": "https://28grams.vip/guide-bread-complete"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how to start sourdough",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "To start a sourdough starter, combine equal parts flour and water by weight in a jar. Feed it daily with the same ratio of flour and water until it becomes bubbly, active, and predictable, which typically takes 7-14 days."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "what is hydration in bread",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Hydration in bread refers to the ratio of water (or other liquids) to flour in a recipe, expressed as a percentage. For example, a dough with 1000g of flour and 750g of water has a 75% hydration. Higher hydration doughs are wetter and typically produce a more open crumb."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "baker's percentage explained",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Baker's percentage is a mathematical method widely used in baking to express the ratio of ingredients to the total flour weight, which is always set at 100%. This allows recipes to be easily scaled up or down."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why did my bread turn out dense and heavy?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A dense crumb is usually caused by under-fermentation, where the dough didn't have enough time to develop gas bubbles. It can also be caused by inactive yeast or an underdeveloped sourdough starter."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Do I really need a Dutch oven to bake sourdough?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "While not strictly necessary, a Dutch oven is highly recommended. It traps the steam escaping from the dough during the first part of the bake, which keeps the crust soft so the bread can expand (oven spring) before the crust sets and hardens."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};

export const meta = {
  title: "The Complete Guide to Bread Baking (From First Loaf to Sourdough)",
  description: "Everything about bread baking: sourdough starters, hydration, baker's percentages, kneading techniques, fermentation science, and troubleshooting common problems.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="28grams"
  title="The Complete Guide to Bread Baking (From First Loaf to Sourdough)"
  description="Everything about bread baking: sourdough starters, hydration, baker's percentages, kneading techniques, fermentation science, and troubleshooting common problems."
  canonical="https://28grams.vip/guide-bread-complete"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-5 py-12">
    <header class="mb-12">
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-6 leading-tight">
        The Complete Guide to Bread Baking <span class="block text-2xl md:text-3xl text-white font-bold mt-2">(From First Loaf to Sourdough)</span>
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed">
        Whether you're about to mix your first simple no-knead loaf or you're deep into the rabbit hole of wild yeast and open crumbs, this is your ultimate manual. We'll cover everything from baker's math to troubleshooting dense doughs.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-8">
      <!-- Table of Contents Sidebar -->
      <aside class="lg:col-span-1 hidden lg:block">
        <div class="sticky top-6 bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-4 uppercase tracking-wider text-sm">Contents</h2>
          <nav class="flex flex-col space-y-3">
            <a href="#getting-started" class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors text-sm">1. Getting Started</a>
            <a href="#bakers-percentages" class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors text-sm">2. Baker's Percentages</a>
            <a href="#hydration" class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors text-sm">3. Hydration</a>
            <a href="#sourdough-101" class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors text-sm">4. Sourdough 101</a>
            <a href="#fermentation" class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors text-sm">5. Fermentation Science</a>
            <a href="#shaping-scoring" class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors text-sm">6. Shaping &amp; Scoring</a>
            <a href="#baking" class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors text-sm">7. Baking &amp; Steam</a>
            <a href="#troubleshooting" class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors text-sm">8. Troubleshooting</a>
            <a href="#faq" class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors text-sm">9. FAQ</a>
          </nav>
        </div>
      </aside>

      <!-- Main Content -->
      <main class="lg:col-span-3 space-y-16">

        <!-- 1. Getting Started -->
        <section id="getting-started" class="scroll-mt-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">1. Getting Started: Your First Simple Loaf</h2>
          <div class="prose prose-invert prose-lg max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
            <p>
              Before diving into complex techniques, the best way to learn bread is simply to make it. The classic no-knead method relies on time rather than elbow grease to develop gluten. Check out our <a href="/guide-bread-baking" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">basic guide to bread baking</a> for a great starting point.
            </p>
            <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-6 rounded-xl my-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-3">The Classic No-Knead Formula</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mb-4">
                <li><strong>500g</strong> Bread Flour</li>
                <li><strong>350g</strong> Warm Water</li>
                <li><strong>10g</strong> Fine Salt</li>
                <li><strong>2g</strong> Instant Yeast (Need to convert fresh or active dry? Use our <a href="/yeast-converter" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">yeast converter</a>)</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm">
                Mix all ingredients until a shaggy dough forms. Cover and let it sit at room temperature for 12-18 hours. Shape into a ball, let it rise for 1-2 hours, and bake in a pre-heated Dutch oven at 450°F (230°C) for 30 minutes covered, then 15 minutes uncovered.
              </p>
            </div>
            <p>
              <strong>What you need:</strong> A kitchen scale (measuring by volume is inaccurate in baking), a large mixing bowl, a bench scraper, and a Dutch oven or cast iron pot with a lid.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 2. Baker's Percentages -->
        <section id="bakers-percentages" class="scroll-mt-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">2. Understanding Baker's Percentages</h2>
          <div class="prose prose-invert prose-lg max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
            <p>
              Once you understand baker's math, you never need a recipe book again. In <a href="/bakers-percentage" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">baker's percentage</a>, the total weight of the flour is always represented as <strong>100%</strong>. Every other ingredient is expressed as a percentage of the flour weight.
            </p>
            <p>
              If a recipe calls for 1000g of flour, 750g of water, and 20g of salt, the baker's percentages are:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 my-4">
              <li>Flour: 100%</li>
              <li>Water: 75% (750 / 1000)</li>
              <li>Salt: 2% (20 / 1000)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              This universal language allows you to scale recipes infinitely, whether you want to bake a single small loaf or fifty loaves for a bakery.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 3. Hydration -->
        <section id="hydration" class="scroll-mt-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">3. Hydration: The Key Variable</h2>
          <div class="prose prose-invert prose-lg max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
            <p>
              <a href="/bread-hydration" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">Bread hydration</a> fundamentally changes the character of your loaf. It is the ratio of liquid to flour.
            </p>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
              <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-5 rounded-xl">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-2">Lower Hydration (60-65%)</h3>
                <p class="text-sm">Stiffer dough, easier to handle, shape, and score. Produces a tighter crumb (perfect for sandwich bread or bagels) and holds its shape well when free-standing.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-5 rounded-xl">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-2">Higher Hydration (75-85%+)</h3>
                <p class="text-sm">Wet, sticky, and difficult to handle. Requires techniques like stretch-and-folds rather than traditional kneading. Yields an open, airy crumb (think ciabatta or rustic sourdough) with a thin, crispy crust.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              <strong>Handling wet dough:</strong> Never add more flour when kneading high-hydration dough. Instead, wet your hands with water or lightly oil your work surface to prevent sticking. Use a bench scraper to build tension.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 4. Sourdough 101 -->
        <section id="sourdough-101" class="scroll-mt-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">4. Sourdough 101</h2>
          <div class="prose prose-invert prose-lg max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
            <p>
              Sourdough doesn't use commercial yeast; it relies on a symbiotic culture of wild yeast and lactic acid bacteria. For a deep dive, check out our dedicated <a href="/guide-sourdough" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">guide to sourdough</a>.
            </p>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Creating & Maintaining a Starter</h3>
            <p>
              Creating a starter takes time and patience. Mix equal parts flour (whole wheat or rye works best initially) and water. Over 7-14 days, you must discard a portion and feed it daily. You can use our <a href="/sourdough-calculator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">sourdough calculator</a> to plan your feeding ratios.
            </p>
            <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-4 rounded-lg my-4 italic">
              "When is it ready?" Your starter is ready to bake with when it reliably doubles (or triples) in volume within 4-8 hours of feeding, and passes the "float test" (a small dollop floats in a glass of water, indicating trapped gas).
            </div>
            <p>
              Want to get scientific about your starter's behavior? Read up on our <a href="/sourdough-study" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">sourdough study</a> to understand how different flours and temperatures affect yeast activity.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 5. Fermentation Science -->
        <section id="fermentation" class="scroll-mt-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">5. Fermentation Science</h2>
          <div class="prose prose-invert prose-lg max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
            <p>
              Fermentation is where the magic happens. It's when yeast consumes starches to produce carbon dioxide (which makes the dough rise) and alcohol/organic acids (which develop flavor). Understanding <a href="/guide-fermentation" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">fermentation principles</a> is what separates good bakers from great ones.
            </p>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Bulk Fermentation vs. Cold Retard</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-3 my-4">
              <li><strong>Bulk Fermentation (First Rise):</strong> Happens at room temperature. This is where the dough develops its structure and volume. You are looking for a percentage increase in volume (often 30-50% for sourdough), not just a specific time. Use a <a href="/fermentation-timer" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">fermentation timer</a> to track your progress, but always watch the dough, not the clock.</li>
              <li><strong>Cold Retard (Second Rise):</strong> After shaping, placing the dough in the fridge (38°F / 3°C) dramatically slows down yeast activity, but the bacteria continue to produce acetic acid. This develops a more complex, sour flavor and makes the dough firmer and easier to score.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              Temperature is an ingredient. A warmer dough ferments much faster than a cold dough. Controlling your water temperature is the easiest way to control your fermentation timeline.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 6. Shaping & Scoring -->
        <section id="shaping-scoring" class="scroll-mt-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">6. Shaping &amp; Scoring</h2>
          <div class="prose prose-invert prose-lg max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
            <p>
              Shaping organizes the gluten network, creating a tight outer "skin" that forces the bread to expand upward (oven spring) rather than outward (pancaking).
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 my-4">
              <li><strong>Boule (Round):</strong> The classic shape. Formed by folding edges into the center and then dragging the dough across the counter to build tension underneath.</li>
              <li><strong>Batard (Oval):</strong> Created by folding the dough into a package and rolling it up tightly into a log shape.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mt-6 mb-3">The Art of Scoring</h3>
            <p>
              Scoring is deliberately cutting the dough to control where it splits as it expands in the oven. Without a score, the bread will burst randomly at its weakest points.
            </p>
            <p>
              Use a sharp razor blade (a lame). A single, deep slash down the middle at a 45-degree angle encourages an "ear" (a raised, crispy flap of crust). More intricate scoring should be shallower.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 7. Baking: Steam, Temp & Timing -->
        <section id="baking" class="scroll-mt-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">7. Baking: Steam, Temperature &amp; Timing</h2>
          <div class="prose prose-invert prose-lg max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
            <p>
              The first 15-20 minutes of baking are crucial. The dough needs a moist, humid environment. Steam keeps the exterior crust pliable, allowing the rapid expansion of gases inside the dough (oven spring) to push the bread up without tearing the crust prematurely.
            </p>
            <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-6 rounded-xl my-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-3">The Dutch Oven Method</h3>
              <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-2 text-sm">
                <li>Place your Dutch oven (with lid) in the cold oven and preheat to 450°F-500°F (230°C-260°C) for at least 45 minutes.</li>
                <li>Carefully transfer your scored dough onto a piece of parchment paper, and lower it into the hot Dutch oven.</li>
                <li>Cover with the lid. The moisture evaporating from the dough is trapped, creating the perfect steamy environment.</li>
                <li>Bake for 20-25 minutes covered.</li>
                <li>Remove the lid. The bread should be fully risen. Lower the temp slightly if needed and bake for another 15-20 minutes to develop a dark, caramelized crust.</li>
              </ol>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 8. Troubleshooting -->
        <section id="troubleshooting" class="scroll-mt-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">8. Troubleshooting Common Problems</h2>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-5 rounded-xl">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Issue: Dense crumb, tunnel-like holes near the top, gummy interior</h3>
              <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] text-sm"><strong class="text-red-400">Diagnosis:</strong> Under-proofed (under-fermented). The yeast didn't have enough time to produce gas throughout the entire dough structure. <br><strong class="text-green-400 mt-1 inline-block">Solution:</strong> Extend bulk fermentation time, ensure your starter is peaking when used, or increase the dough temperature slightly.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-5 rounded-xl">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Issue: Dough is a sloppy, unshapeable puddle that bakes flat</h3>
              <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] text-sm"><strong class="text-red-400">Diagnosis:</strong> Over-proofed (over-fermented). The gluten structure has completely degraded from excessive acid production and gas expansion. <br><strong class="text-green-400 mt-1 inline-block">Solution:</strong> Watch the dough, not the clock. Shorten bulk fermentation, especially on hot summer days. Once over-proofed, bake it in a loaf pan or turn it into focaccia.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-5 rounded-xl">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Issue: Bread lacks "oven spring" but crumb is relatively even</h3>
              <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] text-sm"><strong class="text-red-400">Diagnosis:</strong> Poor shaping tension, lack of steam during the bake, or slightly over-fermented. <br><strong class="text-green-400 mt-1 inline-block">Solution:</strong> Practice shaping techniques to ensure a tight surface skin. Ensure your Dutch oven is preheated thoroughly, and don't skip the steam phase.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 9. FAQ -->
        <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">9. Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <details class="group bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
              <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between gap-1.5 p-5 text-white font-bold">
                how to start sourdough
                <span class="shrink-0 transition duration-300 group-open:-rotate-180">
                  <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5 text-[var(--accent-color)]" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
                </span>
              </summary>
              <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
                <p>To start a sourdough starter, combine equal parts flour and water by weight in a jar. Feed it daily with the same ratio of flour and water until it becomes bubbly, active, and predictable, which typically takes 7-14 days.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details class="group bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
              <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between gap-1.5 p-5 text-white font-bold">
                what is hydration in bread
                <span class="shrink-0 transition duration-300 group-open:-rotate-180">
                  <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5 text-[var(--accent-color)]" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
                </span>
              </summary>
              <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
                <p>Hydration in bread refers to the ratio of water (or other liquids) to flour in a recipe, expressed as a percentage. For example, a dough with 1000g of flour and 750g of water has a 75% hydration. Higher hydration doughs are wetter and typically produce a more open crumb.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details class="group bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
              <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between gap-1.5 p-5 text-white font-bold">
                baker's percentage explained
                <span class="shrink-0 transition duration-300 group-open:-rotate-180">
                  <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5 text-[var(--accent-color)]" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
                </span>
              </summary>
              <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
                <p>Baker's percentage is a mathematical method widely used in baking to express the ratio of ingredients to the total flour weight, which is always set at 100%. This allows recipes to be easily scaled up or down.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details class="group bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
              <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between gap-1.5 p-5 text-white font-bold">
                Why did my bread turn out dense and heavy?
                <span class="shrink-0 transition duration-300 group-open:-rotate-180">
                  <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5 text-[var(--accent-color)]" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
                </span>
              </summary>
              <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
                <p>A dense crumb is usually caused by under-fermentation, where the dough didn't have enough time to develop gas bubbles. It can also be caused by inactive yeast or an underdeveloped sourdough starter.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details class="group bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
              <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between gap-1.5 p-5 text-white font-bold">
                Do I really need a Dutch oven to bake sourdough?
                <span class="shrink-0 transition duration-300 group-open:-rotate-180">
                  <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5 text-[var(--accent-color)]" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
                </span>
              </summary>
              <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
                <p>While not strictly necessary, a Dutch oven is highly recommended. It traps the steam escaping from the dough during the first part of the bake, which keeps the crust soft so the bread can expand (oven spring) before the crust sets and hardens.</p>
              </div>
            </details>
          </div>
        </section>

      </main>
    </div>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
